exec pAT_insertDiffuseText 'DIFSRC_AIR_NH3', 'AIR_NH3_Agriculture.Methodology',1,'NH3, Agriculture, Methodology','<h3>Geographic Information System (GIS) overlay</h3>  <p>Emissions of Ammonia (NH<sub>3</sub>) to air from agriculture have been distributed according to the reporting of the countries to the Convention on Long-Range Transport of Air Pollution (<a target="_blank" href="http://www.eea.europa.eu/data-and-maps/data/national-emissions-reported-to-the-convention-on-long-range-transboundary-air-pollution-lrtap-convention-4">CLRTAP</a>), using the information on animal density (distribution with&nbsp; spatial resolution from FAO and EUROSTAT)and land use information (CORINE).The emissions areallocated using GIS overlay techniques for distribution into grid cells with a spatial resolution of 5x5km&sup2;. The dataset is then transformed into vector polygons and projected into the E-PRTR WGS84 standard projection.</p>  <p>The methodology applied is described in detail in a methodology report which is available <a target="_blank" href="http://147.67.243.36/Public/irc/env/e_prtr/library?l=/prtr_expert_meeting_2/07-agriculturedoc/_EN_1.0_&amp;a=i">here</a>.</p>  <h3>Comparability</h3>  <p>Considerable spatial variation is apparent. The main reasons for the differences are:</p>  <ul>  <li>The spatial pattern of emissions from agricultural activities is dependent on animal density and the spatial pattern of agricultural land use.</li>  </ul>'
